Since

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \frac{1}{1-t} = \sum_{n=0}^\infty t^n\end{align*}

we have

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 
\frac{1}{1+x^3} = \frac{1}{1-(-x^3)} = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-x^3)^n = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^nx^{3n}\end{align*}

Integrating term by term,

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{1}{1+x^3} \ dx &= \int \left(\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^nx^{3n}\right) \ dx \\
&= \sum_{n=0}^\infty \int (-1)^nx^{3n} \ dx \\
&= \left(\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{3n+1}x^{3n+1}\right) + C\end{align*}
